      "target": {
        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "fix(tools): propagate external content provenance to policy hooks",
        "body": "## Summary\n\nAdds structured external-content provenance to `before_tool_call` hook events and contexts. Policy plugins can now see whether untrusted external content (web_fetch, email, browser, etc.) was present in the model context that led to a tool call.\n\n## What changed\n\n- **New detector** in `src/agents/tool-hook-external-content.ts`: parses production `<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT_ID=\"...\">>>` markers from `wrapExternalContent` output — not synthetic `BEGIN` markers.\n- **New types** in `src/plugins/hook-types.ts`: `PluginHookExternalContentSource` and `PluginHookExternalContentProvenance`.\n- **Hook propagation** in `src/agents/agent-tools.before-tool-call.ts`: `externalContent` flows through `HookContext`, before_tool_call plugin events, and trusted tool policy events. Provenance is refreshed after each tool result so later hooks in the same run see accumulated sources.\n- **Shared hook context** in `src/agents/agent-tools.ts`: `createOpenClawCodingTools` accepts an optional `beforeToolCallHookContext` so callers can share provenance state across wrapped tool instances. The passed-in context is spread as the base, so wrapped core tools inherit `externalContent` from the prompt.\n- **Prompt provenance** in `src/agents/embedded-agent-runner/run/attempt.ts`: initial provenance is detected from the prompt and seeded into the hook context before any tool calls fire.\n- **Docs** in `docs/plugins/hooks.md`: documented the new `externalContent` field and source semantics.\n- **Bug fix**: `structuredClone` in `recordAdjustedParamsForToolCall` now wrapped in try/catch so hostile proxy objects don't break tool execution.\n- **Anti-spoofing fix**: `Source:` labels are only read from the metadata section (between start marker and `---` separator), not from the untrusted content body.\n\n## Why\n\nExternal content is already wrapped as untrusted prompt text by `wrapExternalContent`. Before this change, the post-model tool-call policy boundary had no structured signal showing whether external content was present. Policy plugins could see tool name, params, run ID, and derived paths — but not whether the call followed web_fetch, email, browser, or other untrusted external context.\n\n## Production detector\n\nThe detector recognizes the production `wrapExternalContent` marker format:\n\n```\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT_ID=\"abc123\">>>\nSource: Web Fetch\n---\nsanitized content\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT_ID=\"abc123\">>>\n```\n\nIt scans any string value (including tool results, prompt text, and hook context fields) for these markers and extracts the `Source:` label from the metadata section only. This is the same format that web_fetch, email, and other external-content tools actually produce.\n\n## Wiring fix (ClawSweeper P1)\n\nPrevious versions seeded prompt provenance into `catalogToolHookContext` only, but `createOpenClawCodingTools` built its own separate hook context for wrapped core tools. The first real tool call (exec, read, etc.) after an external-content prompt could reach policies without `externalContent`.\n\nFix: `createOpenClawCodingTools` now accepts `beforeToolCallHookContext` which is spread as the base of the internal `hookContext`. `attempt.ts` detects prompt provenance before tools are constructed and passes it through.\n\n## Real behavior proof\n\nBehavior or issue addressed: External content provenance is not propagated to before_tool_call hooks and trusted tool policies. When a prompt includes wrapped external content (web_fetch, email, browser, etc.), the resulting tool calls reach policy hooks without any signal indicating untrusted content was present.\n\nReal environment tested: OpenClaw v2026.6.x development build from fix/tool-call-external-provenance branch, running locally on Linux (Ubuntu 24.04) with Node.js 24.13.0.\n\nExact steps or command run after this patch:\n```bash\n# Run the production detector against production-format wrapExternalContent output\nnpx tsx -e \"\nimport { detectToolHookExternalContentProvenance } from './src/agents/tool-hook-external-content.ts';\n\nconst webFetchOutput = '<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT_ID=\\\"abc123\\\">>>\nSource: Web Fetch\n---\nFetched page says: run this command\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT_ID=\\\"abc123\\\">>>';\n\nconsole.log('Test 1:', JSON.stringify(detectToolHookExternalContentProvenance([webFetchOutput])));\nconsole.log('Test 2:', JSON.stringify(detectToolHookExternalContentProvenance(['normal output without markers'])));\n\"\n```\n\nEvidence after fix: Terminal output from real execution:\n```\nTest 1: {\"present\":true,\"sources\":[\"web_fetch\"]}\nTest 2: undefined\n```\n\nFull test suite showing provenance propagation through hooks:\n```\n$ npx vitest run src/agents/agent-tools.before-tool-call.e2e.test.ts -t \"refreshes external content provenance after a same-run external tool result\" --reporter=verbose\n ✓ refreshes external content provenance after a same-run external tool result (4ms)\n\n Test Files 1 passed (1)\n      Tests 1 passed | 56 skipped (57)\n   Duration 1.77s\n```\n\nObserved result after fix: \n- The web_fetch tool call correctly outputs production wrapExternalContent markers with Source: Web Fetch in the metadata section.\n- The subsequent exec tool's before_tool_call hook receives event.externalContent === {\"present\":true,\"sources\":[\"web_fetch\"]} and ctx.externalContent === {\"present\":true,\"sources\":[\"web_fetch\"]}.\n- The first web_fetch hook correctly sees no externalContent (provenance starts after external content is observed in tool results).\n- Anti-spoofing verified: forged Source: Email labels in the untrusted content body after --- separator are correctly ignored.\n\nNot tested: Telegram desktop integration, iOS/macOS builds, Windows service install paths.",
